------------------------------------------------------------

FILES INCLUDED:

main.cpp:
    Contains the main function. The main function acts as a
    table of contents by displaying the prompt, reading input,
    and sending commands to be processed.

shell.cpp:
    Contains the prompt display function and command handling
    logic. This file parses user input, handles the exit command,
    validates command format, and starts non-pipe commands.

pipe.cpp:
    Contains the pipeCommand function. This file creates pipes,
    forks child processes, redirects input/output using dup2(),
    closes file descriptors, and waits for child processes.

shell.h:
    Header file containing function prototypes used by the project.

Makefile:
    Compiles the project and removes generated files.

README:
    Description and instructions for the project.

------------------------------------------------------------

COMPILATION:

To compile the project:

make

------------------------------------------------------------

RUNNING THE PROGRAM:

To execute the shell:

./xsh

Once running, XSH displays a prompt using the class account
username, such as:

cssc3130%

Valid command formats include:

executablefilename
executablefilename argument
executablefilename | executablefilename
executablefilename | executablefilename | executablefilename
exit

Examples:

ls
ls -l
pwd
ls | sort
ls | sort | cat
exit

------------------------------------------------------------

CLEANING FILES:

To remove executable and object files:

make clean

------------------------------------------------------------

PROGRAM DESCRIPTION:

This program implements an experimental shell named XSH.

The shell:
- Displays a prompt using the USER environment variable
- Reads one command line from the user at a time
- Supports the builtin command exit
- Executes regular commands using fork() and execvp()
- Supports commands with one argument
- Rejects invalid command formats
- Supports pipes between multiple commands
- Uses pipe(), fork(), dup2(), close(), execvp(), and wait()
- Returns to the prompt after each command finishes
- Gracefully exits when the user enters exit

------------------------------------------------------------

DESIGN DECISIONS:

The program was split into multiple source files to keep main()
small and readable.

main.cpp only controls the main shell loop.

shell.cpp handles user input, parsing, validation, and execution
of non-pipe commands.

pipe.cpp handles commands connected by pipes. Each command in a
pipeline is executed in its own child process. Pipes are created
before forking, and dup2() is used to redirect standard input and
standard output.

execvp() was used because it searches the PATH environment
variable for executable names such as ls, pwd, sort, and cat.
This allows both simple command names and path-based execution.

The USER environment variable is used to display the prompt with
the class account username.

System call return values are checked using perror() where
appropriate.

